getThesisList.thesisAbstract: Many systems in nature exhibit spatio-temporal patterns. Mathematically, their spatial distributions are described using the concepts of an order parameter field and the dynamics is modelled using (possibly stochastic) partial-differential equations. Examples of systems which are modelled using field theoretic descriptions are diverse, ranging from fluid flows, nematic liquid crystals, superconductors, ferromagnets to cosmological models of the universe. Field theoretic models can exhibit a variety of defect structures. Defects are tears or discontinuities in the order parameter field. They are also known as topological defects since they are order parameter field solutions that cannot be deformed continuously to the trivial uniform solution. The objective of this thesis is to study the formation and dynamics of topological defects in two dimensional systems.

getThesisList.thesisTitle: En route toward engineering a novel implantable biomaterial for controlled delivery of therapeutics
getThesisList.thesisAbstract: Delivery of therapeutics are highly dependent on the type of drugs administered, their efficacy and safety whilst certain tissues that are hard to reach without achieving high concentrations of potent drugs in blood plasma often accompanied by undesirable systemic side effects. This is not taking into account the clinical complications most drugs exhibit as a result of off-target effects, which deteriorates the patients’ overall clinical status. To solve this problem, our hypothesis was to design a formulation that could locally release potent drugs in a controlled fashion using non-invasive submuscular and peritoneal pocket implants, which ultimately features controlled release of a wide variety of biomolecules in a single dose or sequentially in combination with different drugs. To test our hypothesis in this thesis, we have investigated a number of aims including novel formulations of delivery vehicles that offer high loading efficiency of hydrophilic drugs, hindering burst-release phenomena often observed within 30 minutes of the releasing stage. We have also explored the releasing mechanisms of few different systems leading to the discovery of an important role of interfacial polymer interactions between periphery of nanoparticles and polymer hydrogels that can effectively offer controlled releasing mechanism. We advance by corroborating findings of systems’ in-vitro drug release signatures with materials' rheological behaviors; and finally benchmark our release data using pre-defined mathematical models of the same platforms. We have successfully been able to establish predictive models of our systems with highest confidence, in which future data pattern of drug release with our parameters are likely to be predicted.

getThesisList.thesisTitle: Personalised Health Education using Human Centred Technologies Multimodal Data
getThesisList.thesisAbstract: Obesity and sedentarity in children has increased in the last three decades (Ng et al. 2014). In order to reverse this trend, countries and organisations worldwide implement health education programs for seniors, adults and children, in order to promote behaviour changes and raise awareness with regards to diet and physical activity, two major factors linked to obesity and non-communicable diseases. Health education programs are likely to lead to positive health outcomes, especially when done in childhood (Cecchini et al. 2010), but effectiveness and efficiency varies greatly and the problems are still subsiding. The use of technology in health education programs regarding physical activity and dietary behaviours has shown that computer tailored education seems to have a better effect than other type of non-computer tailored interventions (Kroeze, Werkman, & Brug, 2006), but the subtle mechanisms underlying successful computer tailoring remains unknown. Other types of successful health interventions, for example smoke cessation, have identified that these particular mechanisms in tailored messages are personalization, adaptation or feedback (Dijkstra, 2005). Furthermore, health education programs in physical activity behaviours increasingly use unobtrusive and ubiquitous human centered technologies, especially accelerometers, to measure interventions effectiveness. These technologies provide a new source of data about physical activity that is objective, continuous and precise (rather than self-reported, discrete and approximate). This new source of data can be used as evidence of learning (or change of behaviour) and used for a more refined personalisation, especially when combined with other sources of learning data for example to measure more complex learning tasks (Blikstein & Worsley, 2016) and discover (complex) learning behaviours (Hung & Zhang, 2008). The challenges to work with these data are how capture different modalities, how process them and then how integrate and analyze them to have effectiveness and impact on learning (Ochoa, 2017). In this research we want to answer the question, how can multiple sources of data analytics leverage personalization in physical activity eHealth programs?.
